To check whether it\'s the right answer, the snailfish teacher only
checks the \emph{magnitude} of the final sum. The magnitude of a pair is 3
times the magnitude of its left element plus 2 times the magnitude of
its right element. The magnitude of a regular number is just that
number.

For example, the magnitude of \verb{[9,1]} is \code{3*9 + 2*1 = 29}; the magnitude
of \verb{[1,9]} is \code{3*1 + 2*9 = 21}. Magnitude calculations are recursive:
the magnitude of \verb{[[9,1],[1,9]]} is \code{3*29 + 2*21 = 129}.

Here are a few more magnitude examples:
\itemize{
\item \verb{[[1,2],[[3,4],5]]} becomes \code{143}.
\item \verb{[[[[0,7],4],[[7,8],[6,0]]],[8,1]]} becomes \code{1384}.
\item \verb{[[[[1,1],[2,2]],[3,3]],[4,4]]} becomes \code{445}.
\item \verb{[[[[3,0],[5,3]],[4,4]],[5,5]]} becomes \code{791}.
\item \verb{[[[[5,0],[7,4]],[5,5]],[6,6]]} becomes \code{1137}.
\item \verb{[[[[8,7],[7,7]],[[8,6],[7,7]]],[[[0,7],[6,6]],[8,7]]]} becomes
\code{3488}.
}

